  <h1 class="page-title">First 24 Hours</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    <strong>If something feels wrong, the first day matters.</strong> Stay calm, protect the child, preserve evidence, and take the next right step.
  </p>

  <div id="nav"></div>

  <div class="card hero-warning center-card">
    <h2>Why the first 24 hours matter</h2>
    <div class="rule-box">
      <p>When parents panic, they often move too fast, ask too many questions at once, or delete the very evidence they may later need.</p>
      <p>This page is here to help you slow the panic down and move in the right order.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="danger-line">Calm action protects children better than panic action</div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout center-callout">
    <strong>Start here:</strong><br/>
    Your first job is not to know everything. Your first job is to protect the child, stay calm, and avoid making the situation harder.
  </div>

  <div class="callout center-callout">
    <strong>If this situation is active right now:</strong><br/>
    Focus on safety first, preserve what matters, and move step-by-step below. You do not need the whole answer before you begin protecting the child.
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 1 — Stay calm in front of the child</h2>

    <p class="note">
      Even if you feel sick, angry, shocked, or scared, try not to show panic straight away. Children are far more likely to shut down if they think they are in trouble or if they feel they caused chaos.
    </p>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      <strong>Start with:</strong> “You’re not in trouble. I’m glad you told me. We’ll deal with this together.”
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 2 — Make the child safer immediately</h2>

    <p class="note">
      If the risk is active, reduce contact first. That may mean moving the device closer to you, pausing access to one app, turning off chat, or staying with the child while you assess what is happening.
    </p>

    <p class="note">
      Focus on immediate safety, not punishment.
    </p>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      <strong>Priority:</strong> reduce exposure first, then work out the details.
    </div>

    <div class="btn-grid btn-grid-soft">
      <a class="btn" href="v3-device-controls.html">Device Safety</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-house-rules.html">House Rules</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-parent-scripts.html">What To Say</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-reporting.html">Report &amp; Get Help</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 3 — Do not delete anything yet</h2>

    <p class="note">
      Parents often want to block, delete, wipe chats, remove apps, or throw the phone away immediately. That reaction is understandable, but it can destroy important evidence.
    </p>

    <p class="note">
      If messages, usernames, threats, images, links, or account names are visible, preserve them first.
    </p>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      <strong>Remember:</strong> screenshot first, document first, then decide the next move.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 4 — Preserve the evidence</h2>

    <p class="note">
      Save what you can while it is still visible. Keep it simple and organised.
    </p>

    <ul class="list">
      <li>Screenshot usernames, profiles, chats, threats, and requests</li>
      <li>Capture the app or platform name</li>
      <li>Note the date and time</li>
      <li>Save links, profile names, and group names if visible</li>
      <li>Write down what the child tells you in their own words</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      You are not trying to build a perfect case file. You are trying to stop key details from disappearing.
    </div>

    <div class="btn-grid btn-grid-soft">
      <a class="btn" href="v3-evidence-reporting.html">Save &amp; Report Properly</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-reporting.html">Report &amp; Get Help</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-reporting-australia.html">Australia Reporting</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 5 — Ask calm, simple questions</h2>

    <p class="note">
      Do not launch into a full interrogation. The goal is to understand enough to guide the next step, not force the child to explain everything at once.
    </p>

    <div class="rule-box">
      <p><strong>Helpful questions:</strong></p>
      <p>“Can you show me what happened?”</p>
      <p>“Who is this person?”</p>
      <p>“Did they ask you to move to another app?”</p>
      <p>“Did they ask you to keep anything secret?”</p>
      <p>“Has this happened more than once?”</p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      Keep your tone steady. Children often tell more when they do not feel cornered.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 6 — Do not blame the child</h2>

    <p class="note">
      Even if they broke a rule, hid something, or kept it from you, blame can shut the whole process down. Shame and fear often protect the problem instead of the child.
    </p>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      <strong>Say:</strong> “We’ll sort this out.”<br/>
      <strong>Avoid:</strong> “Why would you do that?” or “I told you this would happen.”
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 7 — Work out what type of situation this is</h2>

    <p class="note">
      You do not need every detail yet, but you do need to sort the situation into the right lane.
    </p>

    <div class="btn-grid btn-grid-soft">
      <a class="btn" href="v3-real-scenarios.html">Real Scenarios</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-what-now.html">What To Do Now</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-redflags.html">Red Flags</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-definitions.html">Understanding What’s Happening</a>
    </div>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      The faster you identify the pattern, the easier it becomes to choose the right response.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>Step 8 — Escalate sooner if the risk is active</h2>

    <p class="note">
      If there are sexual messages, threats, blackmail, coercion, image requests, real-world meet-up talk, or intense emotional pressure, move faster.
    </p>

    <p class="note">
      In those situations, evidence preservation and reporting may matter more than trying to handle it privately.
    </p>

    <div class="btn-grid btn-grid-soft">
      <a class="btn" href="v3-evidence-reporting.html">Save &amp; Report Properly</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-reporting.html">Worldwide Reporting</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-reporting-australia.html">Australia Reporting</a>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="v3-sextortion.html">Sextortion</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>What not to do in the first 24 hours</h2>

    <ul class="list">
      <li>Do not panic in front of the child</li>
      <li>Do not shame or blame them</li>
      <li>Do not delete chats or remove evidence too early</li>
      <li>Do not assume silence means nothing happened</li>
      <li>Do not force a full explanation immediately</li>
      <li>Do not confront the suspected person directly if reporting may matter</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout center-callout">
      The wrong first move can close the child down or erase what you may need later.
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card network center-card">
    <h2>The first 24-hour order</h2>

    <div class="network-flow">
      <div class="pill">Stay calm</div>
      <div class="arrow">↓</div>

      <div class="pill">Protect the child</div>
      <div class="arrow">↓</div>

      <div class="pill">Preserve evidence</div>
      <div class="arrow">↓</div>

      <div class="pill">Ask simple questions</div>
      <div class="arrow">↓</div>

      <div class="pill">Choose the right lane</div>
      <div class="arrow">↓</div>

      <div class="pill danger">Act early, not emotionally</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="card center-card">
    <h2>What to do next from here</h2>

    <p class="note">
      Once you have stabilised the situation, the next step is usually evidence, reporting, or calm guidance for the child.
    </p>

    <div class="btn-grid btn-grid-soft">
      <a class="btn" href="v3-evidence-reporting.html">Save &amp; Report Properly</a>
